{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"What I thought I would talk about today"},{"time":2000,"text":"is the transition from one mode"},{"time":5000,"text":"of thinking about nature"},{"time":7000,"text":"to another that's tracked by architecture. \n\n"},{"time":9000,"text":"What's interesting about architects is, \n\n"},{"time":12000,"text":"we always have tried to justify beauty \n\n"},{"time":15000,"text":"by looking to nature,"},{"time":17000,"text":"and arguably, beautiful architecture \n\n"},{"time":20000,"text":"has always been looking at a model of nature. \n\n"}]},{"cues":[{"time":22000,"text":"So, for roughly 300 years, \n\n"},{"time":25000,"text":"the hot debate in architecture"},{"time":27000,"text":"was whether the number five \n\n"},{"time":29000,"text":"or the number seven"},{"time":31000,"text":"was a better proportion to think about architecture, \n"},{"time":33000,"text":"because the nose was one-fifth of your head, \n\n"},{"time":37000,"text":"or because your head was one-seventh of your body. \n\n"},{"time":40000,"text":"And the reason that that was the model \n\n"},{"time":42000,"text":"of beauty and of nature"},{"time":44000,"text":"was because the decimal point had not been invented yet -- \n\n"},{"time":47000,"text":"it wasn't the 16th century --"},{"time":50000,"text":"and everybody had to dimension a building \n\n"},{"time":53000,"text":"in terms of fractions,"},{"time":55000,"text":"so a room would be dimensioned \n\n"},{"time":57000,"text":"as one-fourth of a facade;"},{"time":59000,"text":"the structural dais of that might be dimensioned as 10 units,"},{"time":63000,"text":"and you would get down to the small elements \n\n"},{"time":66000,"text":"by fractional subdivision: \n\n"},{"time":68000,"text":"finer and finer and finer."}]},{"cues":[{"time":70000,"text":"In the 15th century, the decimal point was invented; \n\n"},{"time":73000,"text":"architects stopped using fractions, \n\n"},{"time":75000,"text":"and they had a new model of nature. \n\n"},{"time":77000,"text":"So, what's going on today \n\n"},{"time":80000,"text":"is that there's a model of natural form"},{"time":83000,"text":"which is calculus-based \n\n"},{"time":85000,"text":"and which is using digital tools,"},{"time":87000,"text":"and that has a lot of implications \n\n"},{"time":89000,"text":"to the way we think about beauty and form, \n\n"},{"time":91000,"text":"and it has a lot of implications in the way we think about nature. \n\n"},{"time":95000,"text":"The best example of this would probably be the Gothic, \n\n"},{"time":98000,"text":"and the Gothic was invented after the invention of calculus, \n\n"},{"time":102000,"text":"although the Gothic architects \n\n"},{"time":104000,"text":"weren't really using calculus to define their forms. \n\n"},{"time":107000,"text":"But what was important is, \n\n"},{"time":109000,"text":"the Gothic moment in architecture was the first time \n\n"},{"time":111000,"text":"that force and motion was thought of in terms of form. \n\n"}]},{"cues":[{"time":115000,"text":"So, examples like Christopher Wren's King's Cross: \n\n"},{"time":118000,"text":"you can see that the structural forces of the vaulting \n\n"},{"time":122000,"text":"get articulated as lines, so you're really actually seeing \n\n"},{"time":125000,"text":"the expression of structural force and form. \n\n"},{"time":128000,"text":"Much later, Robert Maillart's bridges, \n\n"},{"time":131000,"text":"which optimize structural form"},{"time":134000,"text":"with a calculus curvature almost like a parabola. \n\n"},{"time":137000,"text":"The Hanging Chain models of Antonio Gaudi, \n\n"},{"time":141000,"text":"the Catalan architect."},{"time":143000,"text":"The end of the 19th century, beginning of the 20th century, \n\n"},{"time":148000,"text":"and how that Hanging Chain model \n\n"},{"time":150000,"text":"translates into archways\n\n"},{"time":152000,"text":"and vaulting."},{"time":154000,"text":"So, in all of these examples, \n\n"},{"time":156000,"text":"structure is the determining force."},{"time":160000,"text":"Frei Otto was starting to use foam bubble diagrams \n\n"},{"time":163000,"text":"and foam bubble models to generate his Mannheim Concert Hall. \n\n"},{"time":168000,"text":"Interestingly, in the last 10 years"},{"time":171000,"text":"Norman Foster used a similar heat thermal transfer model \n\n"},{"time":175000,"text":"to generate the roof of the National Gallery, \n\n"},{"time":179000,"text":"with the structural engineer Chris Williams. \n\n"}]},{"cues":[{"time":181000,"text":"In all these examples, \n"},{"time":183000,"text":"there's one ideal form, \n"},{"time":185000,"text":"because these are thought in terms of structure. \n\n"},{"time":188000,"text":"And as an architect, I've always found these kinds of systems \n\n"},{"time":191000,"text":"very limiting, because I'm not interested in ideal forms \n\n"},{"time":195000,"text":"and I'm not interested in optimizing to some perfect moment. \n\n"}]},{"cues":[{"time":200000,"text":"So, what I thought I would bring up is \n\n"},{"time":203000,"text":"another component that needs to be thought of, \n\n"},{"time":205000,"text":"whenever you think about nature, \n\n"},{"time":207000,"text":"and that's basically the invention of \n\n"},{"time":209000,"text":"generic form in genetic evolution."},{"time":214000,"text":"My hero is actually not Darwin; \n"},{"time":216000,"text":"it's a guy named William Bateson,\n"},{"time":218000,"text":"father of Greg Bateson, who was here for a long time in Monterey. \n\n"},{"time":223000,"text":"And he was what you'd call a teratologist: \n\n"},{"time":225000,"text":"he looked at all of the monstrosities and mutations \n"},{"time":230000,"text":"to find rules and laws, rather than looking at the norms.\n\n"},{"time":233000,"text":"So, instead of trying to find the ideal type \n\n"},{"time":236000,"text":"or the ideal average,"},{"time":238000,"text":"he'd always look for the exception. So, in this example,\n\n"},{"time":241000,"text":"which is an example of what's called Bateson's Rule, \n\n"},{"time":243000,"text":"he has two kinds of mutations of a human thumb. \n\n"},{"time":247000,"text":"When I first saw this image, 10 years ago, \n\n"},{"time":249000,"text":"I actually found it very strange and beautiful at the same time.\n\n"},{"time":253000,"text":"Beautiful, because it has symmetry. \n\n"},{"time":255000,"text":"So, what he found is that in all cases of thumb mutations, \n\n"},{"time":259000,"text":"instead of having a thumb, \n\n"},{"time":262000,"text":"you would either get another opposable thumb,"},{"time":264000,"text":"or you would get four fingers. \n\n"},{"time":266000,"text":"So, the mutations reverted to symmetry. \n\n"},{"time":269000,"text":"And Bateson invented \n\n"},{"time":271000,"text":"the concept of symmetry breaking,"},{"time":273000,"text":"which is that \n\n"},{"time":275000,"text":"wherever you lose information in a system,"},{"time":278000,"text":"you revert back to symmetry. \n\n"},{"time":280000,"text":"So, symmetry wasn't the sign of order and organization --\n\n"},{"time":284000,"text":"which is what I was always understanding, and as is an architect --\n\n"},{"time":287000,"text":"symmetry was the absence of information. \n\n"},{"time":290000,"text":"So, whenever you lost information, you'd move to symmetry; \n\n"},{"time":292000,"text":"whenever you added information to a system, you would break symmetry.\n\n"},{"time":296000,"text":"So, this whole idea of natural form shifted at that moment \n\n"},{"time":300000,"text":"from looking for ideal shapes \n\n"},{"time":303000,"text":"to looking for a combination of \n\n"},{"time":305000,"text":"information and generic form."}]},{"cues":[{"time":309000,"text":"You know, literally after seeing that image, \n\n"},{"time":312000,"text":"and finding out what Bateson was working with, \n\n"},{"time":315000,"text":"we started to use these rules for symmetry breaking and branching"},{"time":319000,"text":"to start to think about architectural form. \n\n"},{"time":321000,"text":"To just talk for a minute about the \n\n"},{"time":324000,"text":"digital mediums that we're using now \n\n"},{"time":326000,"text":"and how they integrate calculus:"},{"time":329000,"text":"the fact that they're calculus-based \n\n"},{"time":331000,"text":"means that we don't have to think about dimension \n"},{"time":334000,"text":"in terms of ideal units \n\n"},{"time":336000,"text":"or discreet elements."}]},{"cues":[{"time":339000,"text":"So, in architecture we deal with"},{"time":341000,"text":"big assemblies of components, \n\n"},{"time":343000,"text":"so there might be up to, say, \n\n"},{"time":346000,"text":"50,000 pieces of material\n\n"},{"time":348000,"text":"in this room you're sitting in right now"},{"time":350000,"text":"that all need to get organized. \n\n"},{"time":353000,"text":"Now, typically you'd think that they would all be the same: \n\n"},{"time":355000,"text":"like, the chairs you're sitting in would all be the same dimension.\n\n"},{"time":357000,"text":"You know, I haven't verified this, but it's the norm \n\n"},{"time":360000,"text":"that every chair would be a slightly different dimension, \n\n"},{"time":363000,"text":"because you'd want to space them all out for everybody's sight lines. \n\n"},{"time":367000,"text":"The elements that make up the ceiling grid and the lighting, \n\n"},{"time":371000,"text":"they're all losing their modular quality, \n\n"},{"time":374000,"text":"and moving more and more to these infinitesimal dimensions. \n\n"},{"time":377000,"text":"That's because we're all using calculus tools \n\n"},{"time":379000,"text":"for manufacturing and for design. \n\n"}]},{"cues":[{"time":382000,"text":"Calculus is also a mathematics of curves. \n\n"},{"time":386000,"text":"So, even a straight line, defined with calculus, is a curve. \n\n"},{"time":390000,"text":"It's just a curve without inflection."},{"time":392000,"text":"So, a new vocabulary of form\n\n"},{"time":395000,"text":"is now pervading all design fields:"},{"time":398000,"text":"whether it's automobiles, architecture, products, etc.,"},{"time":402000,"text":"it's really being affected by this digital medium of curvature. \n\n"},{"time":405000,"text":"The intricacies of scale that come out of that -- \n\n"},{"time":408000,"text":"you know, in the example of the nose to the face, \n\n"},{"time":411000,"text":"there's a fractional part-to-whole idea. \n\n"},{"time":414000,"text":"With calculus, the whole idea \n\n"},{"time":417000,"text":"of subdivision is more complex,"},{"time":419000,"text":"because the whole and the parts are one continuous series. \n\n"},{"time":423000,"text":"It's too early in the morning for a lecture on calculus, \n\n"},{"time":426000,"text":"so I brought some images to just describe how that works. \n\n"}]},{"cues":[{"time":430000,"text":"This is a Korean church that we did in Queens. \n\n"},{"time":433000,"text":"And in this example, you can see \n\n"},{"time":436000,"text":"that the components of this stair are repetitive, \n\n"},{"time":440000,"text":"but they're repetitive without being modular. \n\n"},{"time":442000,"text":"Each one of the elements in this structure \n\n"},{"time":444000,"text":"is a unique distance and dimension, \n\n"},{"time":448000,"text":"and all of the connections are unique angles. \n\n"},{"time":450000,"text":"Now, the only way we could design that, \n\n"},{"time":452000,"text":"or possibly construct it,"},{"time":455000,"text":"is by using a calculus-based definition \n\n"},{"time":457000,"text":"of the form."},{"time":459000,"text":"It also is much more dynamic, \n\n"},{"time":461000,"text":"so that you can see that the same form opens and closes \n\n"},{"time":464000,"text":"in a very dynamic way as you move across it, \n\n"},{"time":467000,"text":"because it has this quality of vector in motion \n"},{"time":470000,"text":"built into it. \n"},{"time":472000,"text":"So the same space that appears to be a kind of closed volume, \n\n"},{"time":475000,"text":"when seen from the other side becomes a kind of open vista. \n\n"},{"time":479000,"text":"And you also get a sense of\n\n"},{"time":481000,"text":"visual movement in the space,"},{"time":483000,"text":"because every one of the elements is changing in a pattern, \n\n"},{"time":487000,"text":"so that pattern leads your eye towards the altar. \n\n"},{"time":491000,"text":"I think that's one of the main changes, \n\n"},{"time":494000,"text":"also, in architecture: \n\n"},{"time":496000,"text":"that we're starting to look now not for some ideal form,"},{"time":499000,"text":"like a Latin cross for a church, \n\n"},{"time":502000,"text":"but actually all the traits of a church:\n\n"},{"time":504000,"text":"so, light that comes from behind from an invisible source,\n\n"},{"time":508000,"text":"directionality that focuses you towards an altar. \n\n"},{"time":512000,"text":"It turns out it's not rocket science\n\n"},{"time":514000,"text":"to design a sacred space."},{"time":516000,"text":"You just need to incorporate a certain number of traits \n\n"},{"time":519000,"text":"in a very kind of genetic way. \n\n"},{"time":522000,"text":"So, these are the different perspectives of that interior, \n\n"},{"time":524000,"text":"which has a very complex \n"},{"time":526000,"text":"set of orientations all in a simple form. \n"}]},{"cues":[{"time":530000,"text":"In terms of construction and manufacturing, \n\n"},{"time":533000,"text":"this is a kilometer-long housing block \n\n"},{"time":536000,"text":"that was built in the '70s in Amsterdam. \n\n"},{"time":539000,"text":"And here we've broken the 500 apartments\n\n"},{"time":541000,"text":"up into small neighborhoods,"},{"time":544000,"text":"and differentiated those neighborhoods. \n\n"},{"time":546000,"text":"I won't go into too much description of any of these projects, \n\n"},{"time":549000,"text":"but what you can see is that \n\n"},{"time":551000,"text":"the escalators and elevators"},{"time":554000,"text":"that circulate people along the face of the building \n\n"},{"time":557000,"text":"are all held up by \n\n"},{"time":559000,"text":"122 structural trusses."},{"time":563000,"text":"Because we're using escalators\n\n"},{"time":565000,"text":"to move people,"},{"time":567000,"text":"all of these trusses are picking up diagonal loads. \n\n"},{"time":572000,"text":"So, every one of them is a little bit different-shaped \n"},{"time":575000,"text":"as you move down the length of the building. \n\n"},{"time":577000,"text":"So, working with \n"},{"time":579000,"text":"Bentley and MicroStation, \n"},{"time":582000,"text":"we've written a custom piece of software \n\n"},{"time":584000,"text":"that networks all of the components together \n\n"},{"time":587000,"text":"into these chunks of information, \n\n"},{"time":590000,"text":"so that if we change any element \n\n"},{"time":592000,"text":"along the length of the building,"},{"time":594000,"text":"not only does that change distribute \n\n"},{"time":597000,"text":"through each one of the trusses,"},{"time":599000,"text":"but each one of the trusses then distributes that information \n\n"},{"time":602000,"text":"down the length of the entire facade of the building."},{"time":605000,"text":"So it's a single calculation"},{"time":607000,"text":"for every single component of the building\n"},{"time":610000,"text":"that we're adding onto. \n"},{"time":612000,"text":"So, it's tens of millions of calculations"},{"time":616000,"text":"just to design one connection between a piece of structural steel \n\n"},{"time":619000,"text":"and another piece of structural steel. \n\n"},{"time":621000,"text":"But what it gives us is a harmonic \n\n"},{"time":623000,"text":"and synthesized"},{"time":627000,"text":"relationship of all these components, one to another. \n\n"}]},{"cues":[{"time":631000,"text":"This idea has, kind of, brought me into doing \n\n"},{"time":634000,"text":"some product design,"},{"time":636000,"text":"and it's because design firms\n\n"},{"time":639000,"text":"that have connections to architects,"},{"time":641000,"text":"like, I'm working with Vitra, which is a furniture company, \n\n"},{"time":644000,"text":"and Alessi, which is a houseware company.\n\n"},{"time":647000,"text":"They saw this actually solving a problem: \n\n"},{"time":649000,"text":"this ability to differentiate components\n\n"},{"time":651000,"text":"but keep them synthetic."},{"time":654000,"text":"So, not to pick on BMW, \n\n"},{"time":656000,"text":"or to celebrate them,"},{"time":658000,"text":"but take BMW as an example. \n\n"},{"time":660000,"text":"They have to, in 2005,"},{"time":663000,"text":"have a distinct identity \n"},{"time":665000,"text":"for all their models of cars. \n"},{"time":667000,"text":"So, the 300 series, or whatever their newest car is, \n"},{"time":670000,"text":"the 100 series that's coming out, \n\n"},{"time":672000,"text":"has to look like the 700 series,"},{"time":675000,"text":"at the other end of their product line, \n\n"},{"time":678000,"text":"so they need a distinct, coherent identity, \n\n"},{"time":680000,"text":"which is BMW."},{"time":682000,"text":"At the same time, there's a person paying 30,000 dollars\n\n"},{"time":685000,"text":"for a 300-series car, \n\n"},{"time":687000,"text":"and a person paying 70,000 dollars\n\n"},{"time":689000,"text":"for a 700 series,"},{"time":691000,"text":"and that person paying more than double \n\n"},{"time":693000,"text":"doesn't want their car to look too much like \n"},{"time":695000,"text":"the bottom-of-the-market car."},{"time":697000,"text":"So they have to also discriminate between these products. \n\n"},{"time":700000,"text":"So, as manufacturing \n\n"},{"time":702000,"text":"starts to allow more"},{"time":705000,"text":"design options,"},{"time":707000,"text":"this problem gets exacerbated, \n\n"},{"time":709000,"text":"of the whole and the parts."}]},{"cues":[{"time":711000,"text":"Now, as an architect, part-to-whole relationships"},{"time":713000,"text":"is all I think about,\n\n"},{"time":715000,"text":"but in terms of product design"},{"time":717000,"text":"it's becoming more and more of an issue for companies. \n\n"},{"time":720000,"text":"So, the first kind of test product we did \n\n"},{"time":722000,"text":"was with Alessi,"},{"time":724000,"text":"which was for a coffee and tea set. \n\n"},{"time":726000,"text":"It's an incredibly expensive coffee and tea set; \n\n"},{"time":729000,"text":"we knew that at the beginning. So, I actually went to some people I knew\n\n"},{"time":732000,"text":"down south in San Diego, \n\n"},{"time":735000,"text":"and we used an exploded"},{"time":737000,"text":"titanium forming method \n"},{"time":739000,"text":"that's used in the aerospace industry. \n\n"},{"time":742000,"text":"Basically what we can do, \n"},{"time":744000,"text":"is just cut a graphite mold, \n"},{"time":746000,"text":"put it in an oven, heat it to 1,000 degrees, \n\n"},{"time":750000,"text":"gently inflate titanium that's soft, \n\n"},{"time":752000,"text":"and then explode it at the last minute into this form. \n\n"},{"time":755000,"text":"But what's great about it is, \n\n"},{"time":757000,"text":"the forms are only a few hundred dollars. \n\n"},{"time":759000,"text":"The titanium's several thousand dollars, but the forms are very cheap.\n\n"},{"time":762000,"text":"So, we designed a system here \n\n"},{"time":765000,"text":"of eight curves that could be swapped,"},{"time":768000,"text":"very similar to that housing project I showed you, \n\n"},{"time":771000,"text":"and we could recombine those together, \n\n"},{"time":773000,"text":"so that we always had ergonomic shapes \n\n"},{"time":776000,"text":"that always had the same volume"},{"time":779000,"text":"and could always be produced in the same way. \n\n"},{"time":781000,"text":"That way, each one of these tools we could pay for with\n\n"},{"time":783000,"text":"a few hundred dollars, \n\n"},{"time":785000,"text":"and get incredible variation in the components. \n\n"},{"time":788000,"text":"And this is one of those examples of the sets. \n\n"},{"time":791000,"text":"So, for me, what was important is that \n\n"},{"time":793000,"text":"this coffee set --"},{"time":795000,"text":"which is just a coffee pot, a teapot, \n\n"},{"time":797000,"text":"and those are the pots sitting on a tray -- \n\n"},{"time":799000,"text":"that they would have a coherence --\n\n"},{"time":801000,"text":"so, they would be Greg Lynn Alessi coffee pots -- \n\n"},{"time":804000,"text":"but that everyone who bought one \n\n"},{"time":806000,"text":"would have a one-of-a-kind object that was unique in some way. \n\n"}]},{"cues":[{"time":811000,"text":"To go back to architecture, \n\n"},{"time":813000,"text":"what's organic about architecture as a field, \n\n"},{"time":816000,"text":"unlike product design, \n\n"},{"time":818000,"text":"is this whole issue of holism \n\n"},{"time":820000,"text":"and of monumentality is really our realm."},{"time":824000,"text":"Like, we have to design things which are coherent as a single object,\n\n"},{"time":828000,"text":"but also break down into small rooms \n\n"},{"time":831000,"text":"and have an identity of both the big scale \n"},{"time":833000,"text":"and the small scale.\n"},{"time":835000,"text":"Architects tend to work with signature, \n\n"},{"time":839000,"text":"so that an architect needs a signature \n\n"},{"time":841000,"text":"and that signature has to work across the scale of houses \n\n"},{"time":844000,"text":"up to, say, skyscrapers,"},{"time":847000,"text":"and that problem of signatures is a thing we're very good at maintaining\n\n"},{"time":850000,"text":"and working with; and intricacy, \n\n"},{"time":852000,"text":"which is the relationship of, say, \n\n"},{"time":854000,"text":"the shape of a building, its structure, its windows, \n\n"},{"time":857000,"text":"its color, its pattern. These are real architectural problems. \n\n"}]},{"cues":[{"time":862000,"text":"So, my kind of hero for this in the natural world \n\n"},{"time":865000,"text":"are these tropical frogs. \n\n"},{"time":867000,"text":"I got interested in them because they're the most \n\n"},{"time":869000,"text":"extreme example"},{"time":871000,"text":"of a surface where\n\n"},{"time":874000,"text":"the texture and the -- let's call it the decoration --"},{"time":878000,"text":"I know the frog doesn't think of it as decoration, but that's how it works -- \n\n"},{"time":881000,"text":"are all intricately connected to one another.\n\n"},{"time":884000,"text":"So a change in the form \n\n"},{"time":886000,"text":"indicates a change in the color pattern."},{"time":888000,"text":"So, the pattern and the form aren't the same thing, \n\n"},{"time":891000,"text":"but they really work together and are fused\n\n"},{"time":893000,"text":"in some way."},{"time":895000,"text":"So, when doing a center \n"},{"time":898000,"text":"for the national parks in Costa Rica, \n"},{"time":901000,"text":"we tried to use that idea of a gradient color \n\n"},{"time":903000,"text":"and a change in texture"},{"time":906000,"text":"as the structure moves across the surface of the building. \n\n"},{"time":910000,"text":"We also used a continuity of change \n\n"},{"time":913000,"text":"from a main exhibition hall to a natural history museum, \n\n"},{"time":917000,"text":"so it's all one continuous change \n\n"},{"time":919000,"text":"in the massing,"},{"time":921000,"text":"but within that massing are very different kinds of spaces and forms.\n\n"}]},{"cues":[{"time":925000,"text":"In a housing project in Valencia, Spain, we're doing,"},{"time":928000,"text":"the different towers of housing fused together \n\n"},{"time":932000,"text":"in shared curves so you get a single mass, \n"},{"time":935000,"text":"like a kind of monolith,\n"},{"time":937000,"text":"but it breaks down into individual elements. \n\n"},{"time":942000,"text":"And you can see that that change in massing \n\n"},{"time":945000,"text":"also gives all 48 of the apartments \n\n"},{"time":948000,"text":"a unique shape and size,"},{"time":950000,"text":"but always within a, kind of, controlled limit, \n\n"},{"time":953000,"text":"an envelope of change."}]},{"cues":[{"time":957000,"text":"I work with a group of other architects. \n\n"},{"time":959000,"text":"We have a company called United Architects. \n\n"},{"time":961000,"text":"We were one of the finalists for the World Trade Center site design.\n\n"},{"time":965000,"text":"And I think this just shows how \n\n"},{"time":968000,"text":"we were approaching"},{"time":970000,"text":"the problem of incredibly large-scale construction. \n\n"},{"time":973000,"text":"We wanted to make a kind of Gothic cathedral \n\n"},{"time":976000,"text":"around the footprints of the World Trade Center site. \n\n"},{"time":980000,"text":"And to do that, we tried to connect up \n\n"},{"time":983000,"text":"the five towers into a single system."},{"time":987000,"text":"And we looked at, from the 1950s on, \n"},{"time":991000,"text":"there were numerous examples of other architects \n\n"},{"time":993000,"text":"trying to do the same thing."},{"time":995000,"text":"We really approached it at the level \n\n"},{"time":997000,"text":"of the typology of the building,"},{"time":999000,"text":"where we could build these five separate towers, \n\n"},{"time":1001000,"text":"but they would all join at the 60th floor \n\n"},{"time":1004000,"text":"and make a kind of single monolithic mass. \n\n"},{"time":1008000,"text":"With United Architects, also, \n\n"},{"time":1010000,"text":"we made a proposal for the European Central Bank headquarters \n\n"},{"time":1013000,"text":"that used the same system, \n\n"},{"time":1015000,"text":"but this time in a much more monolithic mass, \n\n"},{"time":1017000,"text":"like a sphere."},{"time":1019000,"text":"But again, you can see this, kind of, \n\n"},{"time":1021000,"text":"organic fusion\n\n"},{"time":1023000,"text":"of multiple building elements"},{"time":1025000,"text":"to make a thing which is whole, but breaks down into smaller parts, \n\n"},{"time":1029000,"text":"but in an incredibly organic way. \n\n"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1032000,"text":"Finally, I'd like to just show you \n\n"},{"time":1034000,"text":"some of the effects of using digital fabrication. \n\n"},{"time":1038000,"text":"About six years ago, I bought one of these CNC mills, \n\n"},{"time":1041000,"text":"to just replace, kind of, \n\n"},{"time":1043000,"text":"young people cutting their fingers off all the time building models. \n\n"},{"time":1047000,"text":"And I also bought a laser cutter \n\n"},{"time":1049000,"text":"and started to fabricate within my own shop, \n\n"},{"time":1052000,"text":"kind of, large-scale building elements and models, \n\n"},{"time":1055000,"text":"where we could go directly to the tooling. \n\n"},{"time":1058000,"text":"What I found out is that the tooling, \n\n"},{"time":1061000,"text":"if you intervened in the software, \n\n"},{"time":1063000,"text":"actually produced decorative effects. \n\n"},{"time":1065000,"text":"So, for these interiors, like this shop in Stockholm, Sweden, \n\n"},{"time":1069000,"text":"or this installation wall in the Netherlands \n\n"},{"time":1072000,"text":"at the Netherlands Architecture Institute, \n\n"},{"time":1075000,"text":"we could use the texture that the tool would leave \n\n"},{"time":1078000,"text":"to produce a lot of the spatial effects, \n\n"},{"time":1081000,"text":"and we could integrate the texture of the wall \n\n"},{"time":1083000,"text":"with the form of the wall with the material. \n\n"},{"time":1086000,"text":"So, in vacuum-formed plastic, in fiberglass, \n\n"},{"time":1090000,"text":"and then even at the level of structural steel, \n\n"},{"time":1092000,"text":"which you think of as being linear and modular. \n\n"},{"time":1094000,"text":"The steel industry is so far \n\n"},{"time":1096000,"text":"ahead of the design industry"},{"time":1098000,"text":"that if you take advantage of it \n\n"},{"time":1100000,"text":"you can even start to think of beams and columns \n\n"},{"time":1103000,"text":"all rolled together into a single system"},{"time":1106000,"text":"which is highly efficient,"},{"time":1108000,"text":"but also produces decorative effects\n\n"},{"time":1110000,"text":"and formal effects \n\n"},{"time":1112000,"text":"that are very beautiful and organic."},{"time":1114000,"text":"Thanks very much."}]}]}